The Ministry of Health on Friday announced
that 258 people tested positive for COVID-19 out of 3,206 samples tested in the
past 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 8.0 per cent. Of the cases, 235 are Kenyans while 23 are
foreigners; 142 are males and 116 are females. The youngest case is that
of a three-month-old child and the oldest is 95 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now 333,952 out of 3,760,201 tests conducted
so far. The infections were distributed across
various counties as follows: Nairobi 105, Kiambu 30, Siaya 20, Nakuru 17, Kilifi 12, Nyeri 8, Bungoma
7, Murang’a 7, Busia 6, Laikipia 6, Mombasa 6, Trans Nzoia 5, Kisumu 4, Nyamira
4, Kakamega 2, Machakos 2, Meru 2, Migori 3, Uasin Gishu 3, Bomet, Garissa,
Homa Bay, Kisii, Kwale, Mandera, Narok, Tana River and West Pokot had
one case each. According to Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi
Kagwe, 419 patients have recovered from the disease which has claimed one life
in the past 24 hours. Cumulative fatalities currently stand at 5,653. "There are 134 patients currently
admitted in our health facilities, while 3,793 are under the Home-Based
Isolation and Care program," said Kagwe. "5 patients are in the Intensive Care
Unit (ICU), of whom 4 are on ventilator support while 1 is on supplemental
oxygen. Another 24 are in the General Wards and are all on supplemental oxygen.
No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU)." A total of 18,841,001 vaccines
have also been administered across the country, according to Kagwe. "Of these, 16,775,765 are doses
administered to the adult population (18 years and above). Another 1,543,491 are
doses administered to those between 15 to 17 years, 43,016 are below 15
years but above 12 years while 478,729 are booster doses," said
Kagwe.  "The total number of vaccines
administered in the last 24 hours is 20,128 while the
total number of people fully vaccinated in the last 24 hours is 8,204."